{{Internet-stub}}

An '''e-patient''' is a health consumer who participates fully in his/her medical care, primarily by gathering information about medical conditions that impact them and their families, using the Internet and other digital tools.<ref name="web">{{cite journal |author1=Masters K |author2=Ng'ambi D |author3=Todd, G |title="I Found it on the Internet:" Preparing for the e-patient in Oman |journal=SQU Med J |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=169–179 |year=2010 |url=http://web.squ.edu.om/squmj/includes/tng/pub/tNG_download.asp?id=e5ecd1c850167630052768711a777f70 |doi=10.3923/jms.2010.169.175 |access-date=2010-08-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724202641/http://web.squ.edu.om/squmj/includes/tng/pub/tNG_download.asp?id=e5ecd1c850167630052768711a777f70 |archive-date=2011-07-24 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> The term encompasses those who seek guidance for their own ailments and the friends and family members who go online on their behalf. E-patients report two effects of their health research: "better health information and services, and different, but not always better, relationships with their doctors."<ref>[http://www.pewinternet.org/~/media//Files/Reports/2003/PIP_Health_Report_July_2003.pdf.pdf Fox, Susannah; Fallows, Deborah. 2003. Health searches and email have become more commonplace, but there is room for improvement in searches and overall Internet access.]</ref>
E-patients are active in their care and demonstrate the power of the [[Participatory Medicine]] or [[Health 2.0]] / [[Medicine 2.0]].<ref>Eysenbach G [http://www.jmir.org/2008/3/e22/ Medicine 2.0: Social Networking, Collaboration, Participation, Apomediation, and Openness]. J Med Internet Res 2008;10(3):e22</ref> model of care. The "e" can stand for "''electronic''" but has also been used to refer to other terms, such as "equipped", "enabled", "empowered" and "expert".<ref>{{cite web |author=Kevin Kruse |url=http://blog.kruresearch.com/2009/05/what-do-you-mean-e-patient/ |title=What do you mean, "e-patient"? |publisher=Blog.kruresearch.com |accessdate=2013-09-13 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130825165112/http://blog.kruresearch.com/2009/05/what-do-you-mean-e-patient/ |archive-date=2013-08-25 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref name="jmir.org">{{cite journal|last2=Bond|first2=Carol S|date=8 November 2012|title=What E-patients Want From the Doctor-Patient Relationship: Content Analysis of Posts on Discussion Boards|url=http://www.jmir.org/2012/6/e155/|journal=Journal of Medical Internet Research|volume=14|issue=6|pages=e155|doi=10.2196/jmir.2068|last1=Hewitt-Taylor|first1=Jaqui}}</ref>
The current state of knowledge on the impact of e-patients on the healthcare system and the quality of care received indicates: *A growing number of people say the internet played a crucial or important role as they helped another person cope with a major illness.<ref>[http://www.pewinternet.org/pdfs/PIP_Health_Decisions_2006.pdf Finding Answers Online in Sickness and in Health, 5/2/2006, Pew Internet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306031304/http://www.pewinternet.org/pdfs/PIP_Health_Decisions_2006.pdf |date=2008-03-06 }}.</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Eysenbach G |title=The impact of the Internet on cancer outcomes |journal=CA Cancer J Clin |volume=53 |issue=6 |pages=356–71 |year=2003 |pmid=15224975 |doi=10.3322/canjclin.53.6.356 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.3322/canjclin.53.6.356/full}}</ref> *Many clinicians underestimated the benefits and overestimated the risks of online health resources for [[patients]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Jacobson P |title=Empowering the physician-patient relationship: The effect of the Internet |journal=Partnership: the Canadian Journal of Library and Information Practice and Research |volume=2 |issue=1 |year=2007 |url=http://journal.lib.uoguelph.ca/index.php/perj/article/view/244/374 |issn=1911-9593 |doi=10.21083/partnership.v2i1.244}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ahmad F, Hudak PL, Bercovitz K, Hollenberg E, Levinson W |title=Are Physicians Ready for Patients With Internet-Based Health Information? |journal=Journal of Medical Internet Research |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=e22 |year=2006 |pmid=17032638 |pmc=2018833 |doi=10.2196/jmir.8.3.e22 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Crocco AG, Villasis-Keever M, Jadad AR |title=Analysis of cases of harm associated with use of health information on the internet |journal=JAMA |volume=287 |issue=21 |pages=2869–71 |date=June 2002 |pmid=12038937 |url=http://jama.ama-assn.org/cgi/content/full/287/21/2869 |doi=10.1001/jama.287.21.2869}}</ref> *Medical online [[support group]]s are an important healthcare resource.<ref>{{Cite journal | issn = 1934-1997 | volume = 10 | issue = 2 | page = 46 | last = Feder | first = Judith | last2 = Sands | first2 = Daniel Z. | title = A Reader and Author Respond to "ePatients: Engaging Patients in Their Own Care" | journal = Medscape Journal of Medicine | date = 2008-02-25 | pmid = 18382715 | pmc = 2270894 }}</ref> *“…the net friendliness of clinicians and provider organizations—as rated by the e-patients they serve—is becoming an important new aspect of healthcare quality.”<ref name="firstgen">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.328.7449.1148 | issn = 0959-8138 | volume = 328 | issue = 7449 | pages = 1148–1149 | last = Ferguson | first = Tom | last2 = Frydman | first2 = Gilles | title = The First Generation of E-Patients: These New Medical Colleagues Could Provide Sustainable Healthcare Solutions | journal = British Medical Journal | date = 2004-05-15 |pmid=15142894 |pmc=411079 }}</ref> *According to one study, the advent of patients as partners is one of the most important cultural medical revolutions of the past century.<ref name="firstgen" /> *In order to understand the impact of the e-patient, clinicians will likely need to move beyond "pre-internet medical constructs."<ref name="firstgen" /> *Medical education must adapt to take the e-patient into account, and to prepare students for medical practice that includes the e-patient.<ref name="web" /> A 2011 study of European e-patients found that they tended to be "inquisitive and autonomous" and that they noted that the number of e-patients in Europe appeared to be rising.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Santana|first=Silvina|last2=Lausen|first2=Berthold|last3=Bujnowska-Fedak|first3=Maria|last4=Chronaki|first4=Catherine E.|last5=Prokosch|first5=Hans-Ulrich|last6=Wynn|first6=Rolf|date=2011-04-16|title=Informed citizen and empowered citizen in health: results from an European survey|journal=BMC Family Practice|volume=12|pages=20|doi=10.1186/1471-2296-12-20|issn=1471-2296|pmc=3101118|pmid=21496309}}</ref> A 2012 study found that e-patients uploading videos about their health experienced a loss of privacy, but also positive benefits from social support.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gómez-Zúñiga|first=Beni|last2=Fernandez-Luque|first2=Luis|last3=Pousada|first3=Modesta|last4=Hernández-Encuentra|first4=Eulàlia|last5=Armayones|first5=Manuel|date=2012-04-25|title=ePatients on YouTube: Analysis of Four Experiences From the Patients' Perspective|journal=Medicine 2.0|volume=1|issue=1|doi=10.2196/med2.2039|issn=1923-2195|pmc=4084771|pmid=25075229}}</ref> Furthermore, a 2017 study utilizing social network analysis found that when e-patients are included in health care conferences, they increase information flow, expand propagation, and deepen engagement in the conversation of Tweets when compared to both physicians and researchers while only making up 1.4% of the stakeholder mix.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Utengen|first=Audun|last2=Rouholiman|first2=Dara|last3=Gamble|first3=Jamison G|last4=III|first4=Francisco Jose Grajales|last5=Pradhan|first5=Nisha|last6=Staley|first6=Alicia C|last7=Bernstein|first7=Liza|last8=Young|first8=Sean D|last9=Clauson|first9=Kevin A|date=2017|title=Patient Participation at Health Care Conferences: Engaged Patients Increase Information Flow, Expand Propagation, and Deepen Engagement in the Conversation of Tweets Compared to Physicians or Researchers|url=http://www.jmir.org/2017/8/e280/|journal=Journal of Medical Internet Research|language=en|volume=19|issue=8|doi=10.2196/jmir.8049}}</ref>
